{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610471"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:01:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:01:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16175"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16175"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.95,0,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115217"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8866"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97224"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21118"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115217"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe breast contains specialised cells that are essential for milk production and ejection during lactation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of myoepithelial cells in the breast?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Produce milk proteins and lipids","Contract to eject milk from alveoli","Form the basement membrane of ducts","Secrete hormones that regulate lactation","Transport nutrients into milk-producing cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of myoepithelial cells is to \u003Cstrong\u003Econtract to eject milk from alveoli\u003C/strong\u003E into the ductal system during lactation. These cells contain contractile proteins and respond to oxytocin released during the milk ejection reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduce milk proteins and lipids\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of luminal epithelial cells in the alveoli. \u003Cstrong\u003ESecrete hormones that regulate lactation\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the role of the anterior pituitary and hypothalamus in lactation regulation. While myoepithelial cells sit on the basement membrane, they do not \u003Cstrong\u003Eform the basement membrane of ducts\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransport nutrients into milk-producing cells\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through specific transporters in the cell membranes of milk-producing cells rather than through myoepithelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMyoepithelial cells form a continuous layer between the luminal epithelial cells and basement membrane in both ducts and alveoli. Their contractile function is essential for successful breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Myoepithelial cells in the breast contract to eject milk from the alveoli into the ducts during lactation.","Myoepithelial cells form a continuous layer between the luminal epithelial cells and basement membrane of breast ducts and alveoli."],"references":["Zucca-Matthes G, Urban C, Vallejo A. Anatomy of the nipple and breast ducts. Gland Surg. 2016 Feb;5(1):32-6. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2227-684X.2015.05.10. PMID: 26855906; PMCID: PMC4716863","Javed A, Lteif A. Development of the human breast. Semin Plast Surg. 2013 Feb;27(1):5-12. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1343989. PMID: 24872732; PMCID: PMC3706056","Biswas SK, Banerjee S, Baker GW, Kuo CY, Chowdhury I. The Mammary Gland: Basic Structure and Molecular Signaling during Development. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Mar 31;23(7):3883. doi: 10.3390/ijms23073883. PMID: 35409243; PMCID: PMC8998991","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97224"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16175"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97224"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:07:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:08:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8866"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115217"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"upd